What Porpotion of UOA Students Enagage in Reading and How Can That Relate to IQ?

Introduction

I have taken an observation survey to where I observed the number of students reading books and asked how important reading is to them, if they read in their free time and what their IQ was. This survey was taken over the course of 2 days where I had asked 20 on March 31st 2025 and 20 on May 7th 2025.

Plot 1 - Impact vs. IQ

The plot below describes 3 variables, the IQ groups of students, the rating of how important reading is to that student and filled in with if the student reads in their free time. The colour blue represents if the student does read in their free time and the color red represents if the student does NOT read in their free time. The IQ groups are leveled are increase from minimum to maximum with the students that don’t know their IQ at the bottom. The students that believe reading has a high impact on their life (4/5) are all students that do read in their free time and are clustered on the top right (110-119,120-129,130+), meaning that they possess a high IQ. Students that believe that reading has a low impact on their life (1/2) are mostly students that do NOT read in the free time and are distributed between the IQ groups. This plot can clearly show that most students from UOA that do read and believe that reading is important hold a high IQ. This shows that not only reading in your spare time but reading with intention can be related to intelligence.

Plot 2 - Number of Above Average IQ’s

An above average IQ is 110+. click me for reference The plot below holds the variables count of above average IQ groups(110+) and if the student reads in their free time. The plot’s dataset is a filtered version of plot 1 and all students that have an iq above 110+. The plot describes 2 bars that acquire the the differences in the number of students that posssess an above average IQ and read in their free time. The plot displays to 2 bars the light blue represents student that do read in their free time and the red represents students that don’t. In total in the plot we have 18 students out of the 40 observed that have an above average IQ which is 45% (18/40), within those 18 students 66% of the students read in their free time. and 33% do NOT. This displays that if students from UOA read in their free time they’re likely to obtain or increase their intelligence.

Plot 3 - Number of UOA students that read across 2 dates.

*The data within the dataset has been observed and collected across 2 days and on each day has been collected 2 parts 20 on March 31st and 20 on May 7th. This was done to ensure that there was no bias if the entire 40 rows of data was collected in 1 day. On March 31st the data set shows that students reading in their free time is broken in half with students that do read in their free time and 10 students that don’t. On May 7th the data set shows that students reading in the free time is 13/20 and students that don’t is 7/20. When comparing both days in total the number of students that read in their free time from UOA is 23/40 although this is 57.5% 23/40, the value is still above 50% and we can assume that there are more students from UOA that read in their free time compared to students that don’t.
